  "prompt": "Can foreigners move to Cuba?",
  "response": "Yes, foreigners can move to Cuba, but there are specific regulations and requirements to be aware of. Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **Visa Requirements**: You will need to obtain the appropriate visa to live in Cuba. Depending on your circumstances, you might need a Tourist Visa (Tourist Card), Family Visa, Business Visa, or another type of residency permit.\n\n2. **Residency Permits**: If you plan to stay long-term, you can apply for a residency permit. The process for obtaining residency in Cuba can be complex and typically requires sponsorship from a Cuban citizen, a family member, or an employer. In some cases, retirees can apply for residency through specific programs.\n\n3. **Work Permit**: If you intend to work in Cuba, you must obtain a work permit or working visa. Employment opportunities for foreigners are quite limited and generally require securing a job offer from a Cuban employer.\n\n4. **Investment Opportunities**: Cuba has been opening up to foreign investment in recent years. Investors can seek residency through business ventures or partnerships in designated sectors like tourism, agriculture, and biotechnology.\n\n5. **Healthcare**: Cuban healthcare is available to residents, but it's essential to understand how it works for foreigners. Private healthcare options might also be available.\n\n6. **Cultural Adjustment**: Living in Cuba involves adapting to local customs, culture, and infrastructure. The country has a distinct political and economic system which might differ significantly from what you\u2019re accustomed to.\n\nBefore making any decisions, it\u2019s advisable to consult the Cuban embassy or consulate in your home country for detailed and updated information. Legal advice from professionals experienced in Cuban immigration law can also be very helpful.",
